#MoonKnight has never really fit in, despite trying his hardest to do so. Heâ€™s a black sheep, heâ€™s the guy that other characters snicker about when heâ€™s around, heâ€™s odd, & he marches to the beat of his own drum because he believes what he is doing is the RIGHT thing

Moon Knight has always been the closest thing that encapsulated me in comic book form. I donâ€™t mean the DID, or the resurrection by an Egyptian God, or the violence, or the â€˜toe the lineâ€™ mentality or any of the other comic book stuff, even though those things are super rad

There is a sort of innocence that I am losing in being â€œthe Moon Knightâ€ guy. This isnâ€™t a bad thing. My love and knowledge for the character doesnâ€™t dissipate just because he will be the center of the zeitgeist. Quite the opposite actually.

Iâ€™ve read comics for as long as I could read & comprehend them. I love comics and I love lots of characters, but discovering Moon Knight was life changing. It set my life on a course of fandom I could never have fathomed. I found a guy that â€œnobodyâ€ knew. And he became my guy.

With that being said, I have always flew the Moon Knight flag very proudly. This is might be the last time, outside of creating my own thing, that I will feel this way, as in these fleeting moments before the world is introduced to wacky world of Marc Spector & friends

This is significant for me because for the majority of my life, #MoonKnight has always been MY guy. Granted, I do not own the character & I sure as hell didnâ€™t create him. Iâ€™ve had nothing to do with him creatively. Iâ€™m just a HUGE fan.

We are on the precipice of living in a world where the average, casual Marvel fan will now be fully aware of #MoonKnight & how awesome he is. Regardless of how the show turns out, Iâ€™m left with an extremely weird feeling. One that is hard to equate an adequate comparison for
